# HarmonyOS Harness Toolchain Rules

## Purpose

Use this rule before building, starting, previewing, or diagnosing any app in this workspace.

## Preferred Commands

- Build with `cd <app> && ./dev-build.sh` on macOS/Linux or `cd <app> && dev-build.bat` on Windows.
- Start with `cd <app> && ./dev-start.sh` on macOS/Linux or `cd <app> && dev-start.bat` on Windows.
- Stop local hvigor processes with `cd <app> && ./dev-stop.sh` or `cd <app> && dev-stop.bat`.
- Do not call `hvigorw` directly for normal development work.
- Do not hand-assemble `hdc install` plus `aa start` command chains before trying the app harness scripts.

## Launch And Preflight

- `dev-start.*` is the preferred local development entry.
- `run-start.*` is the release-oriented start path.
- Harness scripts are expected to perform device/simulator preflight before install and launch.
- If no HarmonyOS target is connected, scripts should attempt the root simulator bootstrap first.

## SDK Environment

- SDK setup should flow through the harness `ensure_sdk_environment` logic.
- Do not manually set SDK environment variables in ad hoc commands unless diagnosing the harness itself.
- For SDK failures, inspect the harness output before changing project files.

## Diagnosis Order

When a build or start fails, check in this order:

1. `hvigorw` path and executable availability in the target app or `PATH`.
2. DevEco SDK shim and SDK metadata resolution.
3. `build-profile.json5` at the app and module levels.
4. `oh-package.json5` and dependency installation state.
5. Signing configuration and generated signing artifacts.
6. Harness preflight output for missing target devices, failed install, failed launch, or reported error codes.
7. Runtime logs with `hdc shell hilog -x`.

## Logging

- Use `hdc shell hilog -x` for runtime logs.
- Use `hdc shell aa dump --mission-list` for ability state.
- Avoid adding broad `console.log` noise to app code for issues that the harness or system logs can diagnose.

## Previewer

- Use `cd <app> && ./dev-preview.sh [page]` or `cd <app> && dev-preview.bat [page]` when previewing ArkUI pages.
- Previewer support depends on DevEco Studio and SDK behavior; if preview output is unavailable or inconsistent, fall back to `dev-build.*` plus simulator/device verification and state the limitation.
